Headlines.Headline: Morning commodities commentary

#text: LIVESTOCK:

06/06/00 am: Monday night's close on cutout values ranged from 2 cents lower on the heavy
    select to 15-42 cents higher on the other three. Sales volume was light. Today's trade
    will be moderately active with fair to good buying interest. Sales are expected to be
    light to moderate. Prices will be mixed to higher. Cutouts are expected to close
    steady/higher. Packer offerings will be moderate. Retailer interest should be fairly good
    for ribeyes, sirloin cuts and round cuts for immediate delivery. Sltr Est: 131,000

06/06/00 am: No trade is expected yet today. Packers would have to meet asking prices and
    that's unlikely, particularly since they had good inventories to start this week. Bid-ask
    prices will be clearer today and will likely be 2-4 dlrs apart. Trading is expected to be
    at least light to moderate by Wednesday afternoon, probably in the Cornbelt only. Thursday
    should see the majority of trade at 50 cents to 1 dlr higher. 
    Cattle feeders are generally confident that prices will be higher. Cornbelt: 68-70/111-113
    Kansas: 69-70 Texas: 69-70

06/06/00 am: Cash market for replacement cattle today will be 1-2 dlrs higher than last
    week. Lower corn prices yesterday and buyer optimism for the fed cattle market, as well as
    light to moderate receipts and offerings, will support a strong, active market. Feed cost
    remains generally attractive to most cattle feeders. There is still some concern among
    buyers that corn prices may yet increase since there is a lot of growing season left to
    get through. Plains: 81-92 Cornbelt: 83-93

06/06/00 am: Prices for hogs this morning will be steady to 75 cents higher. Movement was
    good Monday but packers will want another good run today. Monday's cutout value closed 83
    cents higher but did not offset the 1-2 dlrs increase in hog prices. Packers apparently
    expect more increase for pork prices this week. Pork prices should be higher again today.
    Demand for loins has picked up and bellies are trading higher. Hams will be firm; butts,
    weak. Sltr Est: 360,000 Friday: WI Carc: 53-
    72.75 WT: 45.5046.50 EI Carc: 55.75-70 ET: 45.50-46

06/06/00 am: July corn futures closing call: up 2 cents today. The 2000 corn crop was
    rated 71 percent good to excellent vs. 70 percent week-before and 76 percent last year.
    The Kansas State model projects the yield at 143.1 bu./acre vs. USDA at 137, with a
    substantial increase due to early planting. The 6-10 Day Outlook brings heat back into the
    equation, although moisture is expected. Heat is usually crop scare 
    number two and usually around July 4th. We would estimate that about half the Cornbelt has
    inadequate subsoil moisture and will need timely moisture. Iowa was still 71 percent short
    to very short vs. 83 percent week-before. International traders will not offer South Korea
    corn because they have added clause to contracts that cargoes can be 
    rejected if they contain sand, rice bran or straw. This will make Chinese corn more
    expensive. Commitment of traders had the fund net long 6,227 lots vs. 48,107 on May 16.

06/06/00 am: July beans closing call: up 3 cents today. Ratings for the 2000 soybean crop
    were 66 percent, same as week-before, and 70 percent last year. The Kansas State model
    projected the yield at 41.1 bu./acre vs. USDA at 40 bu./acre. There is plenty of time for
    the weather to change several times before the crop is made. China will postpone the
    waiving of the 13 percent value-added tax on meal until June 15 after a meeting with
    domestic crushers on Monday. The U.S. Attach? projected this year's Argentine soybean
    crop at 21 million tonnes, same as USDA and 21 million for 2000-01, but field losses on
    this year's crop can reach 5 to 20 percent of the 6 million tonnes still in the fields.
    
    Commitment of traders revealed the funds net long 13,969 lots of beans vs. 28,525. They
    were net long 102 oil vs. 7,552 and net long 22,473 meal vs. 31,530 on May 16.

06/06/00 am: Chicago July wheat futures closing call: up 2 cents Joday. Kansas City July
    futures closing up 2 cents today. Winter wheat was rated 48 percent vs. 50 week-before and
    67 last year. The Kansas State model projected all winter wheat yields at 45.6 bu./acre
    vs. USDA at 47.5 bu./acre. That would equate to a crop near 1,582 million bushels vs. USDA
    at 1,649 million bushels. Spring wheat ratings were up to 68 from 66 week-before and 73
    last year. The model projected Spring yields at 35.3 bu. vs. USDA at 33.6 bu. Commitment
    of traders indicated the funds net long 10,574 lots on May 30 vs. 14,500 lots on May 16. 
    Australia projected their 2000-01 crop at 22.8 million tonnes vs. USDA at 23 million and
    24.1 million in 1999-2000. The Ukraine crop may be only 11.5 million tonnes vs. 13.5
    million tones last year.

06/06/00 am: July futures: up 25 today. Conditions fell to 49 percent from 54 week-before
    and 52 percent last year. Ratings fell 16 percent in Arkansas, 11 percent in Missouri and
    14 percent in Tennessee. USDA currently has this year's yield at 635 pounds vs. 607 pounds
    last year. The crop was 88 percent planted vs. 86 percent planted average. The 6-10 Day
    Outlook indicates heat, but normal rains in west Texas. Southeast areas will be dry.
    Commitment of traders, futures and options, revealed the funds net long 11,037 lots on May
    30 vs. 8,647 net long May 16.

Headlines.Headline: Pitney Bowes to Sell Leases

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Pitney Bowes
 agreed to sell part of
its large-lease portfolio to GATX for $460 million. The maker of business
equipment also said it will convert other assets into $540 million in cash
through a joint venture with GATX.

Headlines.Author: Rodney Ho
Headlines.Headline: Start-Ups Challenge a Giant

PARAGRAPH.#text:
Since 1920
, Pitney Bowes has had a
virtual lock on the postage-meter industry. But thanks to new technology
and a government push to reduce postage-meter fraud, a number of start-ups
at last see an opportunity to challenge the mail-systems giant.
